                content: "#### Regur Soil Dynamics and Vertical Pore Spaces\nCotton reaches its peak productivity in the deep 'Black Cotton Soils' (Vertisols or Regur) that characterize the Deccan Plateau, known for their exceptional water-holding capacity and high clay content. These soils have the unique ability to 'self-plough' through a cycle of deep cracking in the summer and swelling in the monsoon, which naturally aerates the soil profile. However, for modern high-yield farming, a deep mechanical ploughing (30-45 cm) once every three years is essential to break up 'hard pans' that can restrict the downward growth of the cotton taproot.\n• Drainage Engineering: While cotton loves moisture, it is notoriously sensitive to stagnant water, which can trigger 'reddening' of leaves and root decay within 48 hours. In heavy soils, the land must be formed into a system of ridges and furrows to provide an elevated 'planting zone' that remains aerated even during heavy monsoonal downpours. Maintaining a soil pH between 6.5 and 8.0 is critical; if the soil is too acidic or alkaline, the uptake of vital micronutrients like Zinc and Boron will be blocked, leading to stunted plants and poor boll retention.\n• Cation Exchange Capacity (CEC): Black soils have a high CEC, meaning they can hold onto massive amounts of Calcium and Magnesium. This 'Mineral-Battery' effect is what allows cotton to sustain its aggressive growth for over 180 days. Adding 'Gypsum' (Phospho-Gypsum) at 2 tons/ha can further improve the 'Soil-Flocculation,' making the clay particles clump together and increasing the 'Macro-Pore' space for root respiration during intense rainy spells."
