                content: "#### Spacing Stoichiometry and Depth Control\nPotato seed tubers must be planted at a precise depth of 5-7 cm to ensure they are close enough to the surface for rapid emergence but deep enough to remain moist and protected from temperature fluctuations. The standard spacing of 60×20 cm (row × plant) targets a plant population of approximately 83,333 plants per hectare, which is the mathematical optimum for maximizing the number of 'medium-large' marketable tubers. If planting for 'seed-production,' a closer spacing of 60×15 cm is used to produce a higher proportion of smaller, seed-sized tubers (40-60g).\n• Orientation and Seed-Rate Logistics: Tubers should be placed in the furrow or on the side of the ridge with the 'sprouts facing upward' and the cut surface (if any) facing downward. Covering the tubers immediately with soil from the adjacent furrows is vital to prevent the sprouts from drying out. A standard potato planting requires a massive 'seed-rate' of 20-25 quintals (2000-2500 kg) per hectare, making seed the single largest expense in potato farming. Farmers must ensure that the soil is 'semi-moist' at the time of planting; if the soil is bone-dry, a light 'life-irrigation' should be provided within 24 hours to trigger the first wave of root initiation.\n• The 3-Bud Standard: Each planted tuber or piece must have at least 3 active 'Eyes' to ensure a multi-stemmed hill. Having 3-4 stems per plant ensures a high 'Stolon-Density,' which is the biological driver for a high-yield harvest. Planting in the evening hours reduces the 'Solar-Stress' on the newly exposed seed tubers, keeping the sprouts vigorous and hydrated."
