                title: "Stolon Swelling",
                content: "#### The Thermodynamic Trigger for Tuberization\n'Tuber initiation' is the phase where the plant stops focusing on vertical height and begins redirecting its energy into the swelling of the 'stolon tips.' This transition is governed by a complex interplay of hormones and soil temperature; ideally, soil temperatures must remain between 15-20°C for maximum initiation. If soil temperatures exceed 25°C, the plant will produce massive green foliage but fail to produce a single tuber, a phenomenon often seen in late-planted crops in the plains. Each plant produces 10-15 stolons, but typically only 6-10 will successfully 'set' into tubers.\n• The Stolon-Count Math: The number of tubers initiated now sets the 'absolute-ceiling' for the final yield; later management can only increase the weight of these tubers, not their number. Providing a 'cool-microclimate' through regular, light irrigation is the best technical intervention to maximize the initiation rate. Farmers must also be vigilant for 'Aphids' (small green insects) during this stage, as they act as vectors for viruses that can permanently stunt the 'sink-strength' of the young tubers, leading to a harvest of 'bantam' (undersized) potatoes regardless of the later nutrient inputs.\n• Tuber-Hormone Synergy: The production of 'Tuberonic-Acid' in the leaves is the chemical signal that triggers swelling. Applying a seaweed-based 'Biostimulant' at 45 DAS can synchronize the initiation across the field, ensuring that all tubers grow to a uniform size. A uniform 'Tuber-Set' is critical for mechanical harvesting and ensures that the grade-A percentage of the crop is maximized."
