                title: "Storage Hygiene & Mycotoxin Surveillance",
                content: "#### The Aflatoxin Defense Fence\nStored dried chillies are highly susceptible to 'Aspergillus flavus,' a fungus that produces dangerous 'Aflatoxins.' These toxins are invisible but can lead to total shipment rejection in international markets. To prevent this, the storage room must be kept below 65% Relative Humidity. Using 'Silica-Gel' packets or 'Dehumidifiers' in urban storage spaces is a high-level biosecurity measure that ensures the food safety of the final product.\n• Pest Exclusion (The Cigarette Beetle): The 'Cigarette Beetle' is a common storage pest that bores holes in dried chilli pods. Using 'Pheromone-Disc-Traps' in the storage area provides early warning of an infestation. Once dried to the 'Snap-Point,' sealing the chillies in 'Grain-Pro' (Hermetic) bags effectively suffocates any resident insects, allowing for 100% organic, chemical-free long-term preservation for up to 12 months."
